<subSubSection id="F81B25BF410B6ADC5E96DBC7F98FFF80" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="E5BA73D63C2BE27ED0A2408E3F997B88" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9851D6544F53A6285071C370F21F82B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Observed under dead fungiid coral skeleton and rubble in shallow coral reef. Depth 3-8 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1B2DF76E30864539C6039E0B36E5E45" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="32BF25A6AF8CCC44E17F681EDDF60A81" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="62EF0614AE060880DA6AB81EE59A82FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName id="0F7985C2D58BBF94287FD273855FEFEF" baseAuthorityName="Rudman" baseAuthorityYear="1990" class="Gastropoda" family="Chromodorididae" genus="Verconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Verconia hongkongiensis" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hongkongiensis">
<emphasis id="AE7477AD63DA415AEBB26EC4694768E0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Verconia hongkongiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from Japan and Hong Kong (
<bibRefCitation id="1726853DE3517EF68936B8B390D67093" author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="5D0C083D1E6E162637BA36CCB1CA61CC" author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="New World Publications Inc., Jacksonville" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B96" refString="Gosliner, TM, Valdes, A, Behrens, D, 2018. Nudibranch &amp; Sea Slug Identification - Indo-Pacific. New World Publications Inc., Jacksonville" title="Nudibranch &amp; Sea Slug Identification - Indo-Pacific." year="2018">2018</bibRefCitation>
). The present 
<taxonomicName id="41F61519547691A4C08E00DCD142EAAA" baseAuthorityName="Rudman" baseAuthorityYear="1990" class="Gastropoda" family="Chromodorididae" genus="Verconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Verconia hongkongiensis" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hongkongiensis">Verconia cf. hongkongiensis</taxonomicName>
is a first record for Thai waters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3A127E45D8FB8818182721A64CFD4AD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="E49BD1D442F59127F9EF9C141087AD4E" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CF0DB58ECF8E7236B5365A6EEA0A0287" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Initially recorded as 
<taxonomicName id="644AC329DA5B477A1A2A8E333ABCCC8C" baseAuthorityName="Collingwood" baseAuthorityYear="1881" class="Gastropoda" family="Chromodorididae" genus="Hypselodoris" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hypselodoris bullockii" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bullockii">
<emphasis id="62EA8B5EF417C5D4D3F97C3C7F524FA9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Hypselodoris bullockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Collingwood, 1881) from a single small specimen by 
<bibRefCitation id="9545A6F8E1E14C676A43FCBDB039D85D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" author="Mehrotra, R" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="761 - 771" refId="B161" refString="Mehrotra, R, Scott, CM, 2016. Species inventory of sea slugs (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) for Koh Tao, Thailand, with 25 first records for Thai waters. Marine Biodiversity 46: 761 - 771, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" title="Species inventory of sea slugs (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia) for Koh Tao, Thailand, with 25 first records for Thai waters." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-015-0424-7" volume="46" year="2016">Mehrotra and Scott (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, further observations have concluded that the species from Koh Tao is not 
<taxonomicName id="5FE3246A1C54398196E2B2BEC87A5259" genus="H." lsidName="H. bullockii" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="bullockii">
<emphasis id="0D0AAFDCC97DE7C9B91BEFC06C722F37" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">H. bullockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but one superficially resembling 
<taxonomicName id="D24315D7FAE838A7448E043AC120787C" baseAuthorityName="Rudman" baseAuthorityYear="1990" class="Gastropoda" family="Chromodorididae" genus="Verconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Verconia hongkongiensis" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hongkongiensis">
<emphasis id="6F67C1B337E32579EA105DA1D2F99E97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Verconia hongkongiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="1727AE1F1E7F34D9E4CC37B3200812E6" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1990.tb01864.x" author="Rudman, WB" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="263 - 326" refId="B216" refString="Rudman, WB, 1990. The Chromodorididae (Opisthobranchia: Mollusca) of the Indo-West Pacific: further species of Glossodoris, Thorunna and the Chromodoris aureomarginata colour group. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 100: 263 - 326, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1990.tb01864.x" title="The Chromodorididae (Opisthobranchia: Mollusca) of the Indo-West Pacific: further species of Glossodoris, Thorunna and the Chromodoris aureomarginata colour group." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1096-3642.1990.tb01864.x" volume="100" year="1990">Rudman 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Similarities between the two species are the thin marginal white line and pale variations in colour of the dorsum. However, rather than reddish tips, gills appear to be uniformly red (more orange in some specimens) and rhinophores appear pigmented throughout, basally red, sometimes with a paler median band, ending in red/orange tips, with all individuals recorded from Koh Tao being smaller than 6 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
